"{\n  \"text\": \"Hi everybody, just want to talk real quickly about how the gut bugs talk to each other. This is so interesting. Your cells are defined by their DNA. They they sit in a nucleus and they're protected. That's what they are. Blood cells, bone cells, things like this. But your bacteria, in fact, all bacteria have no nucleases. They're much, much smaller than what's called the eukaryotic cells, which are everything you see around you. But these small little bacteria have no nucleases and they share DNA directly across the cell membrane in what's called lateral gene transfer. This is very important because while you have to reproduce new cells to change them up a little bit, or change them just a little bit in other ways, these bacteria are constantly changing up. And that means they're constantly renewing and reviving based on the conditions and the circumstances and environments. And this is what makes them so dynamic, and this is why it's so important to be constantly giving them new sources of fresh, cool bacteria.\",\n  \"sentences\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \" Hi everybody, just want to talk real quickly about how the gut bugs talk to each other.\",\n      \"start\": 0.32,\n      \"end\": 5.36,\n      \"duration\": 5.04,\n      \"confidence\": 0.996,\n      \"tokens\": [\n        {\n          \"text\": \" Hi\",\n          \"start\": 0.32,\n          \"end\": 0.64,\n          \"duration\": 0.32,\n          \"confidence\": 0.996\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \" ever\",\n          \"start\": 0.72,\n          \"end\": 0.8,\n          \"duration\": 0.08,\n          \"confidence\": 0.999\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"yb\",\n          \"start\": 0.8,\n          \"end\": 0.96,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {\n          \"text\": \"ody\",\n          \"start\": 0.96,\n          \"end\": 1.12,\n          \"duration\": 0.16,\n          \"confidence\": 1.0\n        },\n        {